  "application": "The father promised to assume responsibility for the son student loans if the son married the politician daughter within eighteen months. The son performed the requested act by marrying within fourteen months. That marriage was the bargained for price of the father promise and constitutes consideration because the son was not under a legal duty to marry that specific person within that time period; the fact that the son already intended to propose does not eliminate consideration because the father conditioned his promise on the marriage and the son completed the condition. The lack of a writing raises a Statute of Frauds concern because the promise involves paying another person debt. However, the father was primarily motivated by obtaining a personal economic benefit in the form of a tax deduction, which is a personal pecuniary advantage. That primary purpose makes the promise an original undertaking rather than a collateral promise to guarantee another debt, taking it outside the Statute of Frauds writing requirement. The eighteen month time frame does not independently require a writing under the one year provision because the agreement was capable of being fully performed within one year, and in fact was performed within fourteen months. The father later discovery that no tax deduction was available is a unilateral mistake about the financial consequences of the promise and does not, by itself, excuse performance or negate enforceability.",
  "conclusion": "Yes. The father oral promise is enforceable because the son provided consideration by marrying within the specified time and the promise is not barred by the Statute of Frauds due to the father primary purpose of obtaining a personal economic benefit."
}

