  "application": "The father offered to assume responsibility for the son student loans if the son married the politician daughter within eighteen months, and the son accepted by performing the condition when he married within fourteen months. The son marriage constitutes a legal act and can supply consideration if it was bargained for as the price of the father promise; the fact that the son already planned to propose does not eliminate consideration because performing a requested legal act can be consideration even if the promisee was otherwise inclined to do it, so long as it was requested as part of the exchange. However, the bargain here makes marriage itself the consideration for the father promise, so the agreement is a promise made in consideration of marriage and ordinarily must be evidenced by a signed writing to be enforceable; there was no writing. In addition, the father promise is to pay the son existing student loan debt, which is a promise to answer for the debt of another and ordinarily requires a signed writing as well. The father expected tax deductions, which is a potential personal economic benefit, but the main purpose exception requires that the father principal object be to secure a direct personal economic advantage from the transaction; helping the son and influencing the son marriage choice are not the type of direct economic benefit that typically satisfies the exception, and an anticipated tax deduction based on paying another person debt is not shown to be the kind of bargained for benefit flowing from the creditor relationship that would convert the promise into the father own obligation. Even if the father motivation were economic, the lack of a writing for a marriage consideration promise independently bars enforcement. The father later discovery that no tax deduction was available is a unilateral mistake and does not by itself make the promise unenforceable, but the promise is already unenforceable due to the Statute of Frauds requirements.",
  "conclusion": "No. The father oral promise is not enforceable because it is a promise made in consideration of marriage and also a promise to pay the debt of another, both of which generally require a signed writing, and no applicable exception is sufficiently supported by the facts."
