s unlikely to qualify as the kind of direct, bargained for, primary economic benefit that satisfies the main purpose doctrine, especially where the deduction turned out not to exist and the father’s benefit was not secured by the son’s performance. The father’s later discovery about the tax deduction does not itself excuse performance if a valid contract existed, but the Statute of Frauds prevents enforcement of the oral suretyship promise in the first place.",
